{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}} [[Image:Francesco cirio.jpg|thumb|Francesco Cirio.]] '''Francesco Cirio''' (24 December 1836 – 9 January 1900) was an Italian businessman, and is credited with being one of the first in the world with developing the appertization technique in [[Italy]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Francesco Cirio 1856-1867|url=http://www.cirio1856.us/1856.htm|publisher=Cirio|quote=Francesco Cirio was amongst the first in the world to be credited with developing the appertization technique (the inventor was Frenchman Nicolas Appert).|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727205717/http://www.cirio1856.us/1856.htm|archivedate=27 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Appertization is the method of processing vegetables that leads to them being canned. The term comes from [[Nicolas Appert]], who invented the first process for using heat to sterilize food.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nicolas Appert (c1750 - 1841)|url=http://www.brooklyn.cuny.edu/bc/ahp/MBG/MBG4/Appert.html|publisher=City University of New York}}</ref>
Cirio was born in [[Nizza Monferrato]], then part of the [[Kingdom of Sardinia]], to a poor and illiterate family. When he was 14 years old he came to the capital of the kingdom, Turin. In 1856, Cirio started preserving [[tomato]]es in [[tin]] cans in order for them to be exported. He created his own company (later named Cirio), and when he was 20 years old, he started his first factory in Turin. In 1861, he added further plantations and production facilities in Southern Italy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cirio, A Brief History|url=http://randvimports.com/v2/cirio/|publisher=R and V Imports|quote=He heard that Italian expatriates longed to buy vegetables from home and so developed the concept of putting vegetables in cans and this was the birth of the can food industry.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Michael Bateman|title=Food and Drink: Canny Cooking|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/food--drink-canny-cooking-1046288.html|publisher=''The Independent''|date=January 10, 1999|quote=It is Italy's major food company, founded by Francesco Cirio, father of the canning industry in Turin in the 1860s.}}</ref> In 1867, Cirio exhibited his products in [[Paris]] at the [[International Exposition (1867)|Exposition Universelle]], where he received prestigious awards.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cirio since 1856|url=https://ciaogusto.com/index.php?option=com_zoo&task=item&item_id=25&Itemid=585|publisher=Ciao Gusto|quote=In 1867 Francesco presented his first products in Paris at the Exposition Universelle, where he received prestigious awards.|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018073629/https://ciaogusto.com/index.php?option=com_zoo&task=item&item_id=25&Itemid=585|archivedate=18 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
The company was transformed in 1885 into Societa Anonima di Esportazione Agricola Francesco Cirio in Turin. This company very soon opened subsidiaries in [[Milan]], [[Naples]], [[Belgrade]], Berlin, [[Brussels]], London, Paris, and [[Vienna]]. Cirio also worked to help the agricultural development of Southern Italy.
